evilla, Andalusia, Spain","Vestfold, Norway":"Vestfold, Norway","Kirkwall, Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kirkwall, Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom","Bergen, Norway":"Bergen, Norway","Norway":"Norway","Tønsberg, Norway":"Tønsberg, Norway","Rein, Rissa, Sør-Trøndelag, Norway":"Rissa Prestegjeld, Sør-Trøndelag, Norway","Elsberg, Oslfold, Norway":"Norway","Tønsberg, Vestfold, Norway":"Tønsberg, Vestfold, Norway","nameMeanings":[{"name":"REIN","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Dieter, Dietrich, Erna, Fritz, Gerda, Hedwig, Klaus, Manfred, Wolfgang.","German and Dutch: from a short form of any of various personal names formed with the ancient Germanic element <i>ragin</i> ‘counsel’, for example   Reinbold  , <i>Reinhard</i> (see   Reinhardt  ).","German: variant of   Rain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Reinsel","meanings":["Probably from a pet form of German   Rein   or   Reins   parallel to   Leitzel   and   Reitzel   using the diminutive <i>-el</i>."]},{"name":"Reinbold","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Kurt, Erwin, Goetz, Hans, Ignatz, Johann, Markus, Otto.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>ragin</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’. Compare   Rainbolt   and   Reinbolt  ."]},{"name":"Reinoehl","meanings":["German (<b>Reinöhl</b>): from an elaborated form of <i>Reinel</i>, a pet form of   Rein   1."]},{"name":"Reins","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alfons, Dieter, Gerhardt, Kurt.","North German and Dutch: patronymic from   Rein   1."]},{"name":"Rine","meanings":["Probably an altered form of German   Rein  ,   Rhine  , or   Rhein  ."]},{"name":"Reining","meanings":["North German: patronymic from   Rein   1."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Skulesdatter REIN Queen of Norway was born in 1198, in Norway. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with King Haakon Haakonsson of Norway. She died in 1270, in Rissa Prestegjeld, Sør-Trøndelag, Norway, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1198–1270":"1198–1270","1204–1263":"1204–1263","1226–1226":"1226–1226","1232–1257":"1232–1257","1234–1262":"1234–1262","1238–1280":"1238–1280","10 November 1232":"10. november 1232","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","30 April 1257":"30. aprill 1257","after 1226":"pärast 1226","1238":"1238","1226":"1226","1204":"1204","16 December 1263":"16. detsember 1263","1257":"1257","1234":"1234","1 May 1238":"1. mai 1238","1232":"1232","Sevilla, Andalusia, Spain":"Sevilla, Andalucía, Hispaania","Vestfold, Norway":"Vestfold, Norra","Kirkwall, Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kirkwall, Orkney, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Bergen, Norway":"Bergen, Norra","Norway":"Norra","Tønsberg, Norway":"Tønsberg, Norra","Rein, Rissa, Sør-Trøndelag, Norway":"Rissa Prestegjeld, Sør-Trøndelag, Norra","Elsberg, Oslfold, Norway":"Norra","Tønsberg, Vestfold, Norway":"Tønsberg, Vestfold, Norra"},"fi":{"1198–1270":"1198–1270","1204–1263":"1204–1263","1226–1226":"1226–1226","1232–1257":"1232–1257","1234–1262":"1234–1262","1238–1280":"1238–1280","10 November 1232":"10. marraskuuta 1232","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","30 April 1257":"30. huhtikuuta 1257","after 1226":"1226 jälkeen","1238":"1238","1226":"1226","1204":"1204","16 December 1263":"16. joulukuuta 1263","1257":"1257","1234":"1234","1 May 1238":"1. toukokuuta 1238","1232":"1232","Sevilla, Andalusia, Spain":"Sevilla, Andalucía, Espanja","Vestfold, Norway":"Vestfold, Norja","Kirkwall, Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kirkwall, Orkney, Skotlanti, Yhdi